<div class="header">
  <div class="header-content">
    <div class="tag">Compiled by Gemini 3.1</div>
    <h1>U.S. Bancorp (USB)<br/>Intrinsic Value</h1>
    <p class="subtitle">A transparent, two-stage discounted cash flow valuation of U.S. Bancorp. — using FY2025 actuals, disclosed assumptions, and one final number.</p>
    <p class="date">Updated {meta.published} · Data: FY2025</p>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="container">
  <!-- ═══ THE VERDICT ═══ -->
  <div class="verdict-card">
    <div class="verdict-label">Estimated Intrinsic Value Per Share</div>
    <div class="verdict-price">${roundedIV.toFixed(2)}</div>
    <div class="verdict-vs">vs. market price of ${currentPrice.toFixed(2)} ({marginOfSafety}%)</div>
    <div class="verdict-badge" style={`background: ${verdictColor}22; color: ${verdictColor}; border: 1px solid ${verdictColor}44;`}>
      {verdictText}
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ KEY METRICS ═══ -->
  <div class="stats-row">
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">${rev2025 !== null ? (rev2025 / 1000).toFixed(1) : 'N/A'}B</div>
      <div class="stat-label">FY2025 Revenue</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">${ocf2025 !== null ? (ocf2025 / 1000).toFixed(1) : 'N/A'}B</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Operating Cash Flow</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">${eps2025 !== null ? eps2025.toFixed(2) : 'N/A'}</div>
      <div class="stat-label">EPS (Diluted)</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">${netInc2025 !== null ? (netInc2025 / 1000).toFixed(1) : 'N/A'}B</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Net Income</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">${(netCash / 1000).toFixed(1)}B</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Net Cash vs Debt</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ METHODOLOGY ═══ -->
  <h2>Methodology: Two-Stage DCF (Bank Adaptation)</h2>
  <p>We use a <strong>two-stage discounted cash flow (DCF)</strong> model. However, because U.S. Bancorp is a bank, traditional Free Cash Flow (FCF) metrics are skewed by customer deposits and lending activities. Therefore, we use <strong>Operating Cash Flow</strong> as our proxy for the base cash generation of the business.</p>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">1</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Start with Operating Cash Flow</h4>
      <p>U.S. Bancorp generated <strong>${(ocf2025 !== null ? ocf2025 : 0).toLocaleString()} million</strong> in operating cash flow in FY2025. This metric best represents the cash generated from the core banking operations before major investing and financing activities.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">2</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Project OCF growth for 5 years (Phase 1)</h4>
      <p>We grow OCF at <strong>3% per year</strong> for 5 years. This reflects the mature, steady-state growth expected of a major regional bank, keeping pace with general economic growth and inflation.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">3</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Calculate terminal value (Phase 2)</h4>
      <p>After Year 5, we assume OCF grows at <strong>2% forever</strong> — roughly matching long-term inflation targets. We use the <strong>Gordon Growth Model</strong>: Terminal Value = OCF₆ ÷ (discount rate − terminal growth rate).</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">4</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Discount everything to present value</h4>
      <p>All future cash flows are discounted at <strong>10%</strong> — our required rate of return. This incorporates the current 10Y Treasury yield (4.18%) plus a substantial equity risk premium for the banking sector's inherent regulatory and credit risks.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">5</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Add net cash, divide by shares</h4>
      <p>Enterprise Value + Net Cash = Equity Value. Divide by shares outstanding ({(shares2025 !== null ? shares2025 : 0).toLocaleString()} million) for the per-share intrinsic value.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ THE THREE ASSUMPTIONS ═══ -->
  <h2>The Three Assumptions That Drive Everything</h2>
  <p>A DCF is only as good as its inputs. We're making exactly <strong>three</strong> judgment calls — everything else is math. Here's what we chose and why.</p>

  <div class="assumption-grid">
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">OCF Growth Rate (Years 1-5)</div>
      <div class="value">3%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        As a mature super-regional bank, explosive growth is unlikely and risky. A 3% growth rate models steady loan growth, stable net interest margins, and ongoing cost controls, tracking slightly above long-term inflation.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Discount Rate (WACC)</div>
      <div class="value">10%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        10Y Treasury: 4.18%. Equity risk premium: ~5.8%. While USB is historically well-managed, banking inherently involves leverage and credit risk. A 10% discount rate provides a solid hurdle rate for investing in financial equities.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Terminal Growth Rate</div>
      <div class="value">2%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        In perpetuity, a bank cannot outgrow the broader economy without taking on excessive risk. A 2% terminal growth rate assumes USB maintains its market share while growing alongside GDP and inflation.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

