  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>

  <h3>Upside risks (our number could be too low)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Interest Rate Margins:</strong> If net interest margins (NIM) expand unexpectedly due to favorable yield curve shifts, core earnings and cash flow could significantly exceed our 3% growth proxy.</li>
    <li><strong>Fee Income Growth:</strong> Faster than expected growth in payments, wealth management, and corporate trust services (areas where USB is strong).</li>
    <li><strong>Acquisition Synergies:</strong> Full realization of synergies from past acquisitions (like MUFG Union Bank) could drive greater efficiency than modeled.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks (our number could be too high)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Credit Losses:</strong> A recession could cause a spike in non-performing loans and provision expenses, deeply impacting net income and cash flows.</li>
    <li><strong>Regulatory Capital Requirements:</strong> Tighter regulations (e.g., Basel III endgame rules) could force USB to hold more capital, reducing return on equity and limiting dividend/buyback capacity.</li>
    <li><strong>Deposit Flight:</strong> Increased competition for deposits could compress net interest margins as the bank is forced to pay higher rates to retain funding.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why use Operating Cash Flow instead of Free Cash Flow for a bank?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Traditional Free Cash Flow (Operating Cash Flow - CapEx) is heavily distorted for banks because changes in customer deposits and loans flow through the cash flow statement. CapEx is also a minor part of a bank's operations. Operating Cash Flow provides a clearer, albeit imperfect, proxy for the cash-generating ability of the core business before major balance sheet adjustments.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why a 10% discount rate?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">The 10-year Treasury yields 4.18%. For banks, we demand a solid equity risk premium to compensate for the inherent leverage, credit risk, and economic sensitivity of the business model. 10% provides an appropriate hurdle rate.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Is this a buy recommendation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">No. This is an analytical framework for estimating intrinsic value. Whether to buy depends on your personal risk tolerance, portfolio allocation, and conviction in the assumptions.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

